<i>Adalberht</i> (see   Albert  ).","French: perhaps a metonymic occupational name for someone who made or wore a mailcoat, French <i>haubert</i>, from Old French <i>halberc</i>, <i>hauberc</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Hubert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Lucien, Armand, Normand, Olivier, Adlore, Alphonse, Andre, Benoit, Camil, Camille, Fernand.","German, Dutch, English, French, Walloon, Breton, Polish, Czech, Slovak, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. The name was borne by an 8th-century Christian saint, bishop of Maastricht, who was adopted as the patron of hunters, and helped to increase the popularity of the personal name, especially in the Low Countries.","History: Jean-François-Barthélemi Hubert from Granville in Manche, France, married Félicité Arsenault in Havre-Aubert, QC, in 1801. Nicolas Hubert <i>dit</i> Lacroix from France married Marguerite Landreau in France <i>c.</i> 1653, died in Montreal, QC, in 1687. René Hubert from Paris, France, married Françoise (de) Lacroix in Quebec City, QC, in 1669. Pierre-Paul Hébert/Hubert from France married Suzanne Laporte in QC <i>c.</i> 1716. — This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Hauberk III Lord of Scaldford was born about 1230, in Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom as the son of William Hauberk II Lord of Stapleford and Unknown. He had at least 1 son with Unknown. He died after 1336, in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1230–after 1336":"umbes 1230–pärast 1336","1230–1336":"1230–1336","–Female":"Surnud","1250–1330":"1250–1330","1210–1327":"1210–1327","1327":"1327","about 1250":"umbes 1250","after 1336":"pärast 1336","1336":"1336","June 1327":"juuni 1327","1210":"1210","1330":"1330","1230":"1230","after 1330":"pärast 1330","1250":"1250","about 1230":"umbes 1230","Stapleford, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Stapleford, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sacldford,Leicestershire,England":"Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sacldford, Leicetsershire,England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Scaldford, Leicestershire,England":"Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1230–after 1336":"noin 1230–1336 jälkeen","1230–1336":"1230–1336","–Female":"Kuollut","1250–1330":"1250–1330","1210–1327":"1210–1327","1327":"1327","about 1250":"noin 1250","after 1336":"1336 jälkeen","1336":"1336","June 1327":"kesäkuu 1327","1210":"1210","1330":"1330","1230":"1230","after 1330":"1330 jälkeen","1250":"1250","about 1230":"noin 1230","Stapleford, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Stapleford, Leicestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Sacldford,Leicestershire,England":"Leicestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Sacldford, Leicetsershire,England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Scaldford, Leicestershire,England":"Leicestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1230–after 1336":"environ 1230–après 1336","1230–1336":"1230–1336","–Female":"Déc